## Specifics

### Why add each element?

**Additional Load Balancer (HAProxy Cluster):**
The original single load balancer is itself a Single Point of Failure (SPOF). Adding a second HAProxy instance and configuring them in a **cluster** (using Keepalived with a Virtual IP / VIP) eliminates this SPOF. The two load balancers share a floating VIP:
- **HAProxy #1** is Active — it processes all incoming traffic.
- **HAProxy #2** is Passive — it monitors HAProxy #1 via a heartbeat signal. If HAProxy #1 fails, Keepalived automatically reassigns the VIP to HAProxy #2 within seconds, making it the new Active node. Users experience no downtime.

**Split Components onto Dedicated Servers:**

| Component | Server | Reason |
|-----------|--------|--------|
| Web Server (Nginx) | Dedicated server | Handles only HTTP/HTTPS requests and static files. Isolated from app logic. Can be scaled independently when static traffic increases. |
| Application Server | Dedicated server | Runs only the business logic (e.g., PHP/Python/Node.js). Isolated from web serving. Can be scaled independently when compute-heavy requests increase. |
| Database Server (MySQL) | Dedicated server | Runs only MySQL. I/O-intensive operations don't compete with web or app processes. Can be tuned specifically for database workloads (large RAM for buffer pool, fast disks). |

---

### Why split components?

**Resource Isolation:**
When all components share one server, a memory leak in the application server starves Nginx and MySQL of RAM, degrading all services at once. On separate servers, a problem in one component does not affect others.

**Independent Scaling:**
If the application logic is the bottleneck (CPU-heavy), you can add more application servers without duplicating web servers or databases. This horizontal scaling is only possible when components are decoupled.

**Easier Maintenance:**
Restarting the application server (e.g., to deploy new code) does not interrupt Nginx (which can continue serving cached static content) and does not restart MySQL. Zero-downtime deployments become much simpler.

**Security:**
Each server can have its own firewall with minimal exposed ports. The database server's port 3306 is accessible only from the application server's IP — never from the internet.

---

## Summary of the Full Scaled Infrastructure

| Layer | Component | Count | Notes |
|-------|-----------|-------|-------|
| DNS | foobar.com A record | 1 | Points to Load Balancer VIP |
| Load Balancing | HAProxy cluster | 2 | Active-Passive, Keepalived VIP |
| Web Serving | Nginx | 2+ | Reverse proxy + static files |
| Application | App Server | 2+ | Business logic, horizontally scalable |
| Database | MySQL Primary + Replica | 2 | Primary for writes, Replica for reads |
| Security | Firewalls + SSL | Per layer | HTTPS end-to-end, restricted ports |
| Monitoring | Datadog/Sumologic agents | Per server | Metrics, logs, alerting |

This architecture eliminates all single points of failure, allows each layer to scale independently, and follows the separation of concerns principle.
